In order to further examine potential patterns of mode effects, χ2 tests were performed separately for a number of subgroups, which were defined by gender, age, race, employment status, household income, education level, marital status, urbanity of residence, and length of stay in the Gallup panel (see Table 1
). Within most of these subgroups, the web survey was found to consistently produce lower unit response rates with the exception of the under 35-year-old age group. Interestingly, for this age group (n = 5,026), the response rate for the web survey was slightly higher, 48.7% vs. 45.7% for mail; χ2 = 4.3, df = 1, p = .038, ES (Cohen’s d) = 0.06. However, the positive effect of web mode on survey unit response was limited, in that the effect of the web mode became negative once the 23 sociodemographic covariates (except age dummy variables) were introduced (i.e., Model 2 in Table 2
).

The web survey was found to consistently produce lower item nonresponse rates across sociodemographic subgroups (see Table 4
). This finding was consistent across gender, age, and race groups, as well as across residential variables (home ownership and urbanicity), educational, income, employment and marital status, and length of duration in the Gallup panel. Poisson regression analyses were conducted to examine the effect of mode on item nonresponse before and after introducing controls for each of these sociodemographic characteristics. Model 1 in Table 5
 confirmed that the web survey mode produced a significantly lower number of missing items compared to the mail survey mode. The negative effect of the web survey mode on item nonresponses remained even after applying the multivariate controls for sociodemographic characteristics (i.e., Model 2 in Table 5). In this analysis, each of the sociodemographic measures examined continued to also have independent effects on item nonresponse.
